Diagnosis.
Holotype
16 mm
long for 46 chaetigers, body uniformly dark brown (
Fig. 4A, B
). Lateral antennae as long as the prostomium; median antenna very short; palps bi-articulated as long as lateral antennae, palpostyle twice as long as palpophore; two pairs of elliptical, orange eyes, anterior ones larger (
Fig. 3A, B
). Parapodia sub-biramous (
Fig. 3E, F
). Notopodial cirrophores very long, without marked constriction (
Fig. 3E, F
) and embedded fine notoaciculae (
Fig. 3F, G
); notochaetae absent. Neuropodial prechaetal lobe with papilliform projection on its outer margin (
Fig. 3F
); with two supra- (
Fig. 3H, I
) and two subacicular (
Fig. 3L, M
) compound chaetae with long blades; rest neurochaetae with short blades (
Fig. 3J, K, N
). Pygidiun with a pair of long anal cirri (
Fig. 3D
)

Diagnosis.
Holotype
17 mm
log for 50 chaetigers, body uniformly dark brown, with central paler area on prostomium (
Fig. 4C
). Lateral antennae longer than prostomium; median antenna fusiform, 1/4 as long as the lateral ones; palps as long as lateral antennae, palpostyles 2–3 times longer than palpophores; two pairs of elliptical, whitish eyes, anterior ones larger (
Fig. 5A
). Parapodia sub-biramous (
Fig. 5C–F
). Notopodia with long cirrophores, bearing abrupt constriction at two thirds of their length, distal part of cirrophore clearly thinner (
Fig 5E
); notochaetae absent. Neuropodial prechaetal lobe bearing a long triangular projection (
Fig. 5D, E
); two supra-acicular neurochaetae with long blades (
Fig. 5H, I
), rest with short blades (
Fig. 5G
); subacicular neurochaetae with short blades (
Fig. 5J, K
). Pygidiun with a pair of long anal cirri (
Fig. 5B
)

Description of newly collected material.
Largest specimen complete, 
15 mm
long, 2.5 mm wide without parapodial lobes, 36 chaetigers. Prostomium (
Fig. 6A, B
) oval, twice longer than wide. Palps (
Fig. 6B
) biarticulate; palpostyle tapering, palpophores short, stout, conical, one-third as long as palpostyle. Lateral antennae (
Fig. 6B, C
) conical, slightly longer than palps. Median antenna (
Fig. 6B, C
) piriform, very short, one-quarter as long as lateral ones, inserted frontally. Eyes red, large, (
Fig. 6A, B
), oval, lenticulate; anterior eyes clearly larger than posterior ones. Six pairs of tentacular cirri (
Fig. 6C
), long, unequal; cirrophores stout, cylindrical; cirrostyles tapering, longest ones as long as body width. Notopodial lobes absent. Neuropodial lobes rectangular; bearing noticeable triangular prechaetal projection, one third as long as lobe (
Fig. 6D
); with 1–3 (usually 2), stout neuroaciculae, straight, not protruding. Dorsal cirri with irregularly wrinkled or smooth cirrostyles (
Fig. 6D
), slender, 2–3 times longer than body width; cirrophores (
Fig. 6D, E
) truncated cones, half as long as neuropodial lobes, with clear constriction at two thirds of their length. Neurochaetae compound falcigers (up to 40 per bundle), 10–20 supra-acicular, 14–20 sub-acicular, with long or short serrate blades (
Fig. 6F, G
), with unidentate tips bearing thin subdistal tendon. Ventral cirri (
Fig. 6D
) distal, tapering, half as long as parapodial lobes. Pygidium rounded; bearing two anal cirri, longer and stouter than dorsal cirri of last chaetigers. Pharynx muscular, coarse, with subdistal ring; papillae absent. Live specimens with dorsally brown-striped segments and white prostomium (
Fig. 4D
); preserved specimens with colour fading in variable degrees.
